The South African bond market showed little movement ahead of the Reserve Bank&rsquo;s interest rate decision later in the afternoon.Although the Bank&rsquo;s monetary policy committee is widely expected to keep rates on hold, investors will pay close attention to governor Lesetja Kganyago&rsquo;s comments for clues on the path the committee is likely to adopt in the future.At 11.50am the R186 was bid at 8.980%, unchanged from Wednesday and the R207 was bid at 8.200%, also unchanged.US treasuries weakened further on Wednesday ahead of Thanksgiving Day in the US.Yields of the 10-year treasury was at 2.3516% after firming to 2.29% earlier in the week. As recently as June it had stood at 1.5%.US treasuries were rising for good reason, said deVere group analyst Tom Elliott."President-elect Donald Trump is promising to cut taxes, increase spending and deregulate."He said US bond yields could continue to rise, resulting in losses for investors who entered the fixed-income market now."Yields were likely to rise next month on the US Federal Reserve&rsquo;s policy outlook due to Trump&rsquo;s expected expansionary policies," Elliott said.